Hypothesis

H0: avg profit of startup in california - avg profit of startup in new york >= 0 H1: avg profit of startup in california - avg profit of startup in new york < 0

t.test(startup_data$Profit[startup_data$State== "California"], startup_data$Profit[startup_data$State== "New York"], alternative = "less")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  startup_data$Profit[startup_data$State == "California"] and startup_data$Profit[startup_data$State == "New York"]
## t = -0.67066, df = 31.811, p-value = 0.2536
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##      -Inf 15034.56
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  103905.2  113756.4

The p value is more than the significance level of 5%, hence we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

#ANOVA

anovamodel <- aov(Profit ~ R.D.Spend + Marketing.Spend + Administration + State, data = startup_data)
summary(anovamodel)

#Multiple Linear regression

model <- lm(Profit ~ R.D.Spend + Marketing.Spend + Administration + State, data = startup_data)
summary(model)

R&D spend has a significant impact as the p value is less than the significance level, however other variables do not have a significant impact as the p value exceeds the significance level.
